{{Infobox artist | name = Willem van de Velde the Younger | image = Willem van de Velde II (1633-1707) - (by Lodewijk van der Helst, 1672).jpg | caption = Portrait of Van de Velde in 1672 by ''Lodewijk van der Helst'' | birth_name = | birth_date = Baptized {{birth date |1633|12|18|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Leiden]] | death_date = {{death date and age |1707|4|6|1633|12|18|df=y}} | death_place = [[Greenwich]] | nationality = [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] | field = [[Marine painting]] | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | awards = }}
'''Willem van de Velde the Younger''' (bapt. 18 December 1633; died 6 April 1707) was a [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] [[marine painter]].
==Biography== Willem van de Velde was baptised on 18 December 1633 in [[Leiden]], [[Holland]], [[Dutch Republic]].
A son of [[Willem van de Velde the Elder]], also a painter of sea-pieces, Willem van de Velde, the younger, was instructed by his father, and afterwards by [[Simon de Vlieger]], a marine painter of repute at the time, and had achieved great celebrity by his art before he came to [[London]]. By 1673 he had moved to England, where he was engaged by [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], at a salary of £100, to aid his father in "taking and making draughts of sea-fights", his part of the work being to reproduce in color the drawings of the elder Van de Velde. He was also patronized by the [[James II of England|Duke of York]] and by various members of the nobility.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
He died on 6 April 1707 in [[London]], [[England]],{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} and was buried at [[St James's Church, Piccadilly|St. James's Church]].
His brother [[Adriaen van de Velde]] was also an artist.
==Works== [[File:Willem_van_de_Velde_II_-_Dutch_men-o'-war_and_other_shipping_in_a_calm.jpg|thumb|300px|''Dutch men-o'-war and other shipping in a calm''. c. 1665]] {{double image|right|Het Kanonschot - Canon fired (Willem van de Velde II, 1707).jpg|151|De Windstoot - A ship in need in a raging storm (Willem van de Velde II, 1707).jpg|148|The pendants ''The cannon shot'' and ''The gust'' (c. 1680), in the collection of the [[Rijksmuseum Amsterdam]]}}
Most of Van de Velde's finest works represent views off the coast of Holland, with Dutch shipping. His best productions are delicate, spirited and finished in handling, and correct in the drawing of the vessels and their rigging. The numerous figures are tellingly introduced, and the artist is successful in his renderings of sea, whether in calm or storm.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} The ships are portrayed with almost photographic accuracy, and are the most precise guides available to the appearance of 17th-century ships.
There are a number of van de Velde's marine paintings in the [[Wallace Collection]], London, including "The Embarkation of King [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] at [[Scheveningen]], 1660".
